{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612630"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:26:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:26:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16282"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16282"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.62,0.19,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8973"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8973"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6693"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe orbit contains important venous structures that drain blood from the eye and surrounding tissues. Understanding these drainage patterns is clinically significant due to potential infection spread.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the venous drainage pattern of the orbit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No ophthalmic veins drain into the cavernous sinus","Only the superior ophthalmic vein drains into the cavernous sinus","The ophthalmic veins anastomose with the angular vein","Only inferior ophthalmic veins provide orbital drainage","The ophthalmic veins drain directly into the internal jugular vein"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eophthalmic veins anastomose with the angular vein\u003C/strong\u003E, creating an important connection between facial and intracranial venous systems. This anatomical arrangement has clinical significance as it can provide a route for infection spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth superior and inferior ophthalmic veins drain posteriorly into the cavernous sinus, making the statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eno ophthalmic veins drain into the cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect, as is the claim that \u003Cstrong\u003Eonly the superior ophthalmic vein drains into the cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eonly inferior ophthalmic veins provide orbital drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is inaccurate since both superior and inferior ophthalmic veins contribute to orbital drainage. The ophthalmic veins drain into the cavernous sinus first rather than directly into the internal jugular vein, making \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe ophthalmic veins drain directly into the internal jugular vein\u003C/strong\u003E incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe superior ophthalmic vein is typically larger and receives tributaries from the forehead, upper eyelid, and nose. The inferior ophthalmic vein drains the floor of the orbit and lower eyelid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ophthalmic veins include superior and inferior branches that drain posteriorly into the cavernous sinus.","The superior ophthalmic vein forms an important anastomosis with the angular vein, providing a connection between intracranial and facial venous systems.","This venous connection can serve as a route for infection spread between facial and intracranial structures."],"references":["Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16282"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:00:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:01:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8973"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115420"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedA